	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />If you want to turn the SEROM board to SBROM (aka allowing 64kb PRG and 64kb CHR, the maximum available if you only want to deal with 28-pins chips only) you'll only have to disconnect pin 1 to VCC and tie it to PRG A15 on the MMC1, which should be extremely simple to do.
<br />
<br />Why Nintendo did different boards for SEROM and SBROM to me is a complete mystery. I see no reason why a 32kb chip shouldn't work on SBROM (without rewiring). The same question remains for SCROM and SHROM, which seems also identical exept for pin 1 of the PRG.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


